They call me lucky, but I’ve never once chosen where I land.

I was born ordinary—pressed into existence, one of millions, identical, unremarkable. For a while, I lived in darkness, stacked with others like me, clinking softly in a paper roll. Then light. Then motion. Then a pocket.

That’s where the first story began.

⸻

The Runner

He found me in the parking lot.

Face-up. Humans care about that.

He almost didn’t pick me up. He hesitated, looked around like someone might judge him for bending down for a single cent. But he did. Thumb, forefinger—warm, uncertain—and then I was his.

He rubbed me once against his shirt. A small ritual. A quiet hope.

He had a race that day.

Not a big one. No cameras. No crowd screaming his name. Just a local marathon and a personal goal: finish without stopping.

At mile 18, his legs started to fail him. His breathing broke into pieces. His mind began offering exits—reasonable ones. Smart ones.

Then his hand brushed his pocket.

Me.

He remembered bending down. Remembered choosing to pick me up. Something about that stuck with him. A decision made for no reason.

“If I can do that,” he thought, “I can do this.”

He didn’t get faster. He didn’t win.

But he didn’t stop.

Luck, for him, wasn’t speed.

It was continuation.

⸻

I left him that night.

Laundry has a way of redistributing fate. I slipped from his pocket into a machine, spun through water and noise, and ended up somewhere else entirely.

⸻

The Waitress

She found me in the dryer lint tray.

Didn’t even smile.

She was tired in a way that didn’t go away with sleep. Bills stacked higher than hope. Tips had been thin for weeks. She picked me up without thinking and dropped me into her apron.

I stayed there through a double shift.

Orders. Smiles she didn’t feel. Coffee refills. Apologies that weren’t her fault.

Near closing, a man came in late. Not rude, not kind. Just distracted. He ordered something simple. Ate quickly. Left.

She almost missed it.

The tip.

Not large. Not life-changing.

But it was written strangely on the receipt. A note:

“You didn’t rush me. I needed that.”

She stood still for a moment.

Then she folded the receipt and put it in her pocket—with me.

Luck, for her, wasn’t money.

It was being seen.

⸻

Coins travel best when no one is paying attention.

A bus ride. A dropped purse. A sidewalk crack.

That’s how I reached him.

⸻

The Kid

He wasn’t supposed to be out that late.

He kicked me before he noticed me. Sent me spinning across the pavement.

He chased me—not because I mattered, but because motion did.

Kids like motion.

When I stopped, he crouched and picked me up.

“Lucky,” he said out loud, like testing the word.

He had a test the next day. One he hadn’t studied for. Not because he couldn’t—but because no one had ever made him believe it mattered.

He held me in his hand for a while. Then he flipped me.

Heads.

He smiled.

“Okay,” he said to no one. “I’ll try.”

He went home. Opened a book. Read one page. Then another. Not much. Not everything.

But enough.

The next day, he didn’t ace the test.

But he passed.

Luck, for him, wasn’t brilliance.

It was starting.

⸻

I’ve been in fountains, pockets, gutters, and jars labeled “just in case.” I’ve been thrown away and found again. Lost more times than I can count.

People think I carry luck.

I don’t.

I carry moments.

Small ones. Easy to ignore. Easy to dismiss. A bend at the waist. A glance downward. A pause long enough to choose something slightly different.

That’s where luck lives.

Not in me.

In them.

I’m just the excuse.